div.p:
That the President’s French-granted autocratic legislative and executive powers
                    are exercised under the firm control of General Collet with General Catroux’s
                    support and General de Gaulle’s approval;

That consequently such important matters as national defense, police sûreté, censorship, supply services and intérêts communs (revenues from customs, oil refinery, monopolies, et
                    cetera) are in fact controlled by the French with scantiest regard for and no
                    accounting to the Ministry;

That his Ministry is more than willing to cooperate with Allied control in all
                    matters where limitation of sovereign authority is necessitated by conditions of
                    war; including questions of supply;
